</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H398">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">אָכֹ֥ל</span>
  <span class="word-translit">&#x27;aKhol</span>
  <span class="word-english">they will eat</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h398.html">H398</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9002">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">וְ/הוֹתֵֽר\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">ve/hoTer</span>
  <span class="word-english">and/ they will have more than enough</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9002</span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The servant is using the question form to emphasize that the amount of food is not enough. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [This is not enough food to feed a hundred men!]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> To translate this expression here and in the next verse, see how you translated the similar expression in 4:12. Alternate translation: [shall I put this in front of] or [shall I serve this to]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [Yahweh says that they will have enough to eat, and there will be some left over]
    </div><div class="interlinear-verse hebrew-verse"><span class="verse-num">44</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9001">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">וַ/יִּתֵּ֧ן</span>
  <span class="word-translit">va/iyiTen</span>
  <span class="word-english">and/ he put it</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9001</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9005">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">לִ/פְנֵי/הֶ֛ם</span>
  <span class="word-translit">li/fnei/Hem</span>
  <span class="word-english">to/ before/ them</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9005</span>
